{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775839404402,"sessionID":"ses_287bcb93dffe74sqV2FOvjBYfr","part":{"id":"prt_d7846de00001S6cZeulwAEqaG1","messageID":"msg_d7846bd12001EMAPfRSNd3KqU7","sessionID":"ses_287bcb93dffe74sqV2FOvjBYfr","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_108c96ba6aaa4b0982b8e33f","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_alibaba-cn-qwen3.6-plus_20260410T073331Z/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_alibaba-cn-qwen3.6-plus_20260410T073331Z/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-015: PicoD 命令执行 API — Delta Spec\n2: \n3: ## Context\n4: \n5: - **Module:** `pkg/picod`, `cmd/picod`\n6: - **Language:** Go\n7: - **Size:** M\n8: - **Base specs:** `code-execution/spec.md`, `code-execution/design.md`, `deployment/client-go.md`\n9: \n10: ## Delta Requirements\n11: \n12: ### Requirement: Server configuration and startup\n13: \n14: The system SHALL define a `Config` struct with `Port int` and `Workspace string` fields. The system SHALL parse CLI flags `-port` (default `8080`) and `-workspace` (default `\"\"`). If `workspace` is empty, the workspace root SHALL be resolved to the current working directory via `os.Getwd()`; failure to resolve CWD SHALL be fatal. The HTTP server SHALL use `ReadHeaderTimeout` of 10 seconds. Gin SHALL run in `ReleaseMode` with `gin.Logger()` and `gin.Recovery()` as global middleware.\n15: \n16: #### Scenario: Defaults from CLI\n17: \n18: - **GIVEN** `-port` and `-workspace` flags use program defaults\n19: - **WHEN** the binary starts\n20: - **THEN** `Port` defaults to `8080`, `Workspace` is empty (resolved to CWD at runtime)\n21: - **AND** Gin runs in `ReleaseMode`\n22: \n23: #### Scenario: Custom port and workspace\n24: \n25: - **GIVEN** `-port=9090` and `-workspace=/tmp/picod-workspace`\n26: - **WHEN** `NewServer` is called with the parsed config\n27: - **THEN** `config.Port` is `9090` and `config.Workspace` is `/tmp/picod-workspace`\n28: - **AND** the server listens on `:9090`\n29: \n30: #### Scenario: Empty workspace resolves to CWD\n31: \n32: - **GIVEN** `-workspace` is not provided (empty string)\n33: - **WHEN** `NewServer` initializes\n34: - **THEN** `workspaceDir` is set to the absolute path of the current working directory\n35: \n36: #### Scenario: CWD resolution failure is fatal\n37: \n38: - **GIVEN** `os.Getwd()` returns an error and `config.Workspace` is empty\n39: - **WHEN** `NewServer` attempts to resolve the workspace\n40: - **THEN** the process calls `klog.Fatalf` and does not start serving\n41: \n42: #### Scenario: Non-empty workspace is made absolute\n43: \n44: - **GIVEN** `config.Workspace` is set to a relative path like `./data`\n45: - **WHEN** `setWorkspace` runs\n46: - **THEN** `workspaceDir` is resolved to an absolute path via `filepath.Abs`\n47: \n48: ### Requirement: Route registration\n49: \n50: The system SHALL register routes on a `*gin.Engine` as follows: `GET /health` (no auth), and an `/api` group with `AuthManager.AuthMiddleware` containing `POST /execute`, `POST /files`, `GET /files` (query-based listing), and `GET /files/*path` (wildcard download).\n51: \n52: #### Scenario: Health endpoint is public\n53: \n54: - **GIVEN** a running PicoD server\n55: - **WHEN** a client calls `GET /health` without any `Authorization` header\n56: - **THEN** the request is served without authentication\n57: \n58: #### Scenario: API routes require auth middleware\n59: \n60: - **GIVEN** a running PicoD server\n61: - **WHEN** a client calls `POST /api/execute` without a valid JWT\n62: - **THEN** the `AuthManager.AuthMiddleware` intercepts and returns HTTP 401\n63: \n64: #### Scenario: All five routes are registered\n65: \n66: - **GIVEN** `NewServer` completes successfully\n67: - **WHEN** the route table is inspected\n68: - **THEN** the following routes exist: `GET /health`, `POST /api/execute`, `POST /api/files`, `GET /api/files`, `GET /api/files/*path`\n69: \n70: ### Requirement: Health check response\n71: \n72: The system SHALL respond to `GET /health` with HTTP 200 and JSON containing `status: \"ok\"`, `service: \"PicoD\"`, `version: \"0.0.1\"`, and `uptime` as a string from `time.Since(serverStartTime)`.\n73: \n74: #### Scenario: Unauthenticated health response\n75: \n76: - **GIVEN** no `Authorization` header\n77: - **WHEN** the client calls `GET /health`\n78: - **THEN** the response is HTTP 200 with JSON `{\"status\": \"ok\", \"service\": \"PicoD\", \"version\": \"0.0.1\", \"uptime\": \"<duration>\"}`\n79: \n80: #### Scenario: Uptime increases over time\n81: \n82: - **GIVEN** the server has been running for at least 1 second\n83: - **WHEN** `GET /health` is called\n84: - **THEN** the `uptime` field is a non-zero duration string (e.g. `\"1.234s\"`)\n85: \n86: ### Requirement: JWT authentication middleware\n87: \n88: The system SHALL define an `AuthManager` struct with a `*rsa.PublicKey` field protected by `sync.RWMutex`. The middleware SHALL require the `Authorization` header in `Bearer <token>` format, parse the JWT with RSA public key verification using `jwt.WithExpirationRequired()`, `jwt.WithIssuedAt()`, and `jwt.WithLeeway(time.Minute)`. Non-RSA signing methods SHALL be rejected. On success, the request body SHALL be wrapped with `http.MaxBytesReader` limiting size to `MaxBodySize` (32 MiB).\n89: \n90: #### Scenario: Missing Authorization header\n91: \n92: - **GIVEN** no `Authorization` header is present\n93: - **WHEN** an `/api` route is hit\n94: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 401 with JSON `{\"error\": \"...\", \"code\": 401, \"detail\": \"...\"}`\n95: \n96: #### Scenario: Malformed Authorization header\n97: \n98: - **GIVEN** `Authorization` header is not two space-separated parts or does not start with `Bearer`\n99: - **WHEN** the middleware runs\n100: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 401 with JSON error indicating invalid format\n101: \n102: #### Scenario: Valid RSA JWT passes\n103: \n104: - **GIVEN** a valid JWT signed with the corresponding RSA private key, not expired, with `iat` claim\n105: - **WHEN** the middleware runs\n106: - **THEN** `c.Request.Body` is wrapped with `http.MaxBytesReader(..., MaxBodySize)` and `c.Next()` is called\n107: \n108: #### Scenario: Expired JWT is rejected\n109: \n110: - **GIVEN** a JWT whose `exp` claim is in the past (beyond 1 minute leeway)\n111: - **WHEN** the middleware runs\n112: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 401 with `error: \"Invalid token\"` and `detail` containing the verification error\n113: \n114: #### Scenario: Non-RSA signing method rejected\n115: \n116: - **GIVEN** a JWT signed with HS256 (HMAC)\n117: - **WHEN** the key function asserts `token.Method` is `*jwt.SigningMethodRSA`\n118: - **THEN** the type assertion fails and the middleware returns HTTP 401\n119: \n120: ### Requirement: Public key loading from environment\n121: \n122: The system SHALL load the RSA public key from the `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` environment variable. The value SHALL be PEM-decoded and parsed via `x509.ParsePKIXPublicKey`, asserting the result is `*rsa.PublicKey`. If the env var is unset, PEM decoding fails, or the key is not RSA, `LoadPublicKeyFromEnv` SHALL return an error and `NewServer` SHALL call `klog.Fatalf`.\n123: \n124: #### Scenario: Valid PEM public key loaded\n125: \n126: - **GIVEN** `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` contains a valid PEM block with `PUBLIC KEY` type encoding an RSA public key\n127: - **WHEN** `LoadPublicKeyFromEnv` is called\n128: - **THEN** `authManager.publicKey` is set to the parsed `*rsa.PublicKey` and no error is returned\n129: \n130: #### Scenario: Missing environment variable\n131: \n132: - **GIVEN** `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` is unset or empty\n133: - **WHEN** `LoadPublicKeyFromEnv` is called\n134: - **THEN** an error is returned indicating the environment variable is not set\n135: \n136: #### Scenario: Invalid PEM block\n137: \n138: - **GIVEN** `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` contains text that is not valid PEM\n139: - **WHEN** `LoadPublicKeyFromEnv` is called\n140: - **THEN** `pem.Decode` returns nil and an error `failed to decode PEM block` is returned\n141: \n142: #### Scenario: Non-RSA key rejected\n143: \n144: - **GIVEN** `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` contains a valid PEM block encoding an ECDSA public key\n145: - **WHEN** `LoadPublicKeyFromEnv` is called\n146: - **THEN** the type assertion to `*rsa.PublicKey` fails and an error is returned\n147: \n148: #### Scenario: Server refuses to start without key\n149: \n150: - **GIVEN** `LoadPublicKeyFromEnv` returns an error\n151: - **WHEN** `NewServer` initializes\n152: - **THEN** `klog.Fatalf` is called and the process exits\n153: \n154: ### Requirement: Command execution handler\n155: \n156: The system SHALL accept `POST /api/execute` with JSON body binding to `ExecuteRequest`. The handler SHALL run `command[0]` with `command[1:]` as arguments via `exec.CommandContext`, capture stdout and stderr into `bytes.Buffer`, and respond with HTTP 200 and `ExecuteResponse` JSON. The request SHALL NOT accept stdin from the client.\n157: \n158: #### Scenario: Valid execution with default timeout\n159: \n160: - **GIVEN** a valid JWT and JSON body `{\"command\": [\"echo\", \"hello\"]}` with empty `timeout`\n161: - **WHEN** the client calls `POST /api/execute`\n162: - **THEN** the server uses a default timeout of 60 seconds, runs the command, and returns `{\"stdout\": \"hello\\n\", \"stderr\": \"\", \"exit_code\": 0, \"duration\": <float>, \"start_time\": <time>, \"end_time\": <time>}`\n163: \n164: #### Scenario: Custom timeout\n165: \n166: - **GIVEN** JSON body with `\"timeout\": \"500ms\"`\n167: - **WHEN** the handler runs\n168: - **THEN** the command context timeout is set to 500 milliseconds\n169: \n170: #### Scenario: Timeout exceeded\n171: \n172: - **GIVEN** a command that runs longer than the specified timeout (e.g. `sleep 10` with `\"timeout\": \"1s\"`)\n173: - **WHEN** the context deadline is exceeded\n174: - **THEN** `exit_code` is `124` (`TimeoutExitCode`) and `stderr` includes a message that the command timed out with the timeout length formatted as an integer number of seconds\n175: \n176: #### Scenario: Invalid timeout format\n177: \n178: - **GIVEN** `\"timeout\": \"not-a-duration\"`\n179: - **WHEN** the handler attempts to parse the timeout\n180: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with JSON `{\"error\": \"invalid timeout format: ...\", \"code\": 400}`\n181: \n182: #### Scenario: Empty command array\n183: \n184: - **GIVEN** JSON body `{\"command\": []}`\n185: - **WHEN** the handler validates the request\n186: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with `{\"error\": \"command cannot be empty\", \"code\": 400}`\n187: \n188: #### Scenario: Malformed JSON body\n189: \n190: - **GIVEN** the request body is not valid JSON\n191: - **WHEN** `ShouldBindJSON` is called\n192: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with the binder error and `code: 400`\n193: \n194: #### Scenario: Non-zero exit code is captured\n195: \n196: - **GIVEN** a command that exits with code 1 (e.g. `[\"sh\", \"-c\", \"exit 1\"]`)\n197: - **WHEN** the command completes\n198: - **THEN** the response `exit_code` is `1` and the response is HTTP 200\n199: \n200: #### Scenario: Working directory inside workspace\n201: \n202: - **GIVEN** `\"working_dir\": \"subdir\"` and the workspace contains `subdir/`\n203: - **WHEN** the handler resolves the working directory\n204: - **THEN** `cmd.Dir` is set to the sanitized absolute path of `workspaceDir/subdir`\n205: \n206: #### Scenario: Invalid working directory\n207: \n208: - **GIVEN** `\"working_dir\": \"../../etc\"` that would escape the workspace\n209: - **WHEN** `sanitizePath` is called\n210: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with `error` prefixed by `\"Invalid working directory: \"`\n211: \n212: #### Scenario: Environment augmentation\n213: \n214: - **GIVEN** `\"env\": {\"FOO\": \"bar\", \"BAZ\": \"qux\"}`\n215: - **WHEN** the command runs\n216: - **THEN** `cmd.Env` includes `FOO=bar` and `BAZ=qux` in addition to the current process environment\n217: \n218: ### Requirement: File upload handler (multipart)\n219: \n220: The system SHALL detect `Content-Type` with prefix `multipart/form-data` and handle as multipart upload. The handler SHALL read form field `path`, form file `file`, and optional form field `mode`. Parent directories SHALL be created with mode `0755`. The file SHALL be written to a sanitized path with mode from `parseFileMode` (default `0644`).\n221: \n222: #### Scenario: Successful multipart upload\n223: \n224: - **GIVEN** multipart request with `path=\"test/hello.txt\"`, file content `\"world\"`, and `mode=\"0644\"`\n225: - **WHEN** the handler runs\n226: - **THEN** parent directory `test/` is created with mode `0755`, the file is written with mode `0644`, and HTTP 200 returns `{\"path\": \"test/hello.txt\", \"size\": 5, \"mode\": \"-rw-r--r--\", \"modified\": \"<time>\"}`\n227: \n228: #### Scenario: Multipart missing path\n229: \n230: - **GIVEN** multipart request with no `path` form field\n231: - **WHEN** the handler runs\n232: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with JSON error indicating missing path\n233: \n234: #### Scenario: Multipart missing file\n235: \n236: - **GIVEN** multipart request with `path` set but no `file` form field\n237: - **WHEN** the handler runs\n238: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with JSON error indicating missing file\n239: \n240: #### Scenario: File mode exceeds max\n241: \n242: - **GIVEN** multipart upload with `mode=\"07777\"` (exceeds `maxFileMode` of `0777`)\n243: - **WHEN** `parseFileMode` is called\n244: - **THEN** the mode falls back to `0644`\n245: \n246: #### Scenario: Invalid file mode falls back\n247: \n248: - **GIVEN** multipart upload with `mode=\"abc\"`\n249: - **WHEN** `parseFileMode` is called\n250: - **THEN** the mode falls back to `0644`\n251: \n252: ### Requirement: File upload handler (JSON Base64)\n253: \n254: The system SHALL bind non-multipart requests to `UploadFileRequest` with required `path` and `content` (Base64 standard encoding). The handler SHALL decode `content` via `base64.StdEncoding`, create parent directories with mode `0755`, write the file with `parseFileMode` on `mode`, and respond with `FileInfo`.\n255: \n256: #### Scenario: Successful Base64 upload\n257: \n258: - **GIVEN** JSON body `{\"path\": \"data.bin\", \"content\": \"<base64-encoded-bytes>\", \"mode\": \"0755\"}`\n259: - **WHEN** the handler runs\n260: - **THEN** the decoded bytes are written to `workspaceDir/data.bin` with mode `0755` and HTTP 200 returns `FileInfo`\n261: \n262: #### Scenario: Invalid Base64 content\n263: \n264: - **GIVEN** JSON body with `\"content\": \"not-valid-base64!!!\"`\n265: - **WHEN** `base64.StdEncoding.DecodeString` is called\n266: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with JSON error describing invalid base64\n267: \n268: #### Scenario: Empty mode defaults to 0644\n269: \n270: - **GIVEN** JSON body with `\"mode\": \"\"`\n271: - **WHEN** `parseFileMode` is called\n272: - **THEN** the returned `os.FileMode` is `0644`\n273: \n274: ### Requirement: File listing handler\n275: \n276: The system SHALL accept `GET /api/files?path=...`, require the `path` query parameter to be non-empty, read the directory at the sanitized path via `os.ReadDir`, and return `ListFilesResponse` with an array of `FileEntry` objects. Entries where `entry.Info()` fails SHALL be skipped.\n277: \n278: #### Scenario: Successful directory listing\n279: \n280: - **GIVEN** `path=\"\"` (empty string, meaning workspace root) and the workspace contains files\n281: - **WHEN** the client calls `GET /api/files?path=`\n282: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 200 with `{\"files\": [{\"name\": \"...\", \"size\": N, \"modified\": \"...\", \"mode\": \"...\", \"is_dir\": bool}]}`\n283: \n284: #### Scenario: Missing path query parameter\n285: \n286: - **GIVEN** no `path` query parameter or `path` is empty\n287: - **WHEN** the client calls `GET /api/files`\n288: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with `{\"error\": \"Missing 'path' query parameter\", \"code\": 400}`\n289: \n290: #### Scenario: Directory not found\n291: \n292: - **GIVEN** `path=\"nonexistent\"` and the directory does not exist\n293: - **WHEN** `os.ReadDir` is called\n294: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 404 with `{\"error\": \"Directory not found\", \"code\": 404}`\n295: \n296: #### Scenario: Subdirectory listing\n297: \n298: - **GIVEN** `path=\"subdir\"` and `subdir/` exists inside the workspace\n299: - **WHEN** the handler runs\n300: - **THEN** entries within `subdir/` are returned as `FileEntry` objects\n301: \n302: #### Scenario: Entries with stat errors are skipped\n303: \n304: - **GIVEN** a directory containing an entry where `entry.Info()` returns an error\n305: - **WHEN** the handler iterates entries\n306: - **THEN** the problematic entry is omitted from the response and no error is returned\n307: \n308: ### Requirement: File download handler\n309: \n310: The system SHALL serve file contents at `GET /api/files/*path`. The wildcard path parameter SHALL be trimmed of its leading `/` before sanitization. The handler SHALL set download-oriented headers (`Content-Description: File Transfer`, `Content-Transfer-Encoding: binary`, `Content-Disposition: attachment; filename=\"<basename>\"`, `Content-Type` from `mime.TypeByExtension` or `application/octet-stream`) and stream the file via `c.File`.\n311: \n312: #### Scenario: Successful file download\n313: \n314: - **GIVEN** a regular file exists at `workspaceDir/docs/readme.md`\n315: - **WHEN** the client calls `GET /api/files/docs/readme.md`\n316: - **THEN** the response includes `Content-Disposition: attachment; filename=\"readme.md\"`, appropriate `Content-Type`, and the file body\n317: \n318: #### Scenario: Path escapes workspace\n319: \n320: - **GIVEN** `GET /api/files/../../etc/passwd`\n321: - **WHEN** `sanitizePath` is called\n322: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with JSON error describing access denied / workspace jail violation\n323: \n324: #### Scenario: Path is a directory\n325: \n326: - **GIVEN** the wildcard path resolves to a directory inside the workspace\n327: - **WHEN** the handler checks the file type\n328: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with `{\"error\": \"Path is a directory, not a file\", \"code\": 400}`\n329: \n330: #### Scenario: File not found\n331: \n332: - **GIVEN** the path does not exist\n333: - **WHEN** `os.Stat` fails with `os.IsNotExist`\n334: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 404 with `{\"error\": \"File not found\", \"code\": 404}`\n335: \n336: #### Scenario: Unknown extension defaults to octet-stream\n337: \n338: - **GIVEN** a file with no recognized extension (e.g. `data.blob`)\n339: - **WHEN** `mime.TypeByExtension` is called\n340: - **THEN** `Content-Type` is set to `application/octet-stream`\n341: \n342: ### Requirement: Path sanitization (sanitizePath)\n343: \n344: The system SHALL implement `sanitizePath` with the following algorithm: (1) if `workspaceDir` is empty, return error `workspace directory not initialized`; (2) resolve `workspaceDir` via `filepath.EvalSymlinks`, falling back to `filepath.Abs` or `filepath.Clean` on error; (3) clean the resolved workspace; (4) clean the input path, stripping leading `os.PathSeparator` if absolute; (5) join with resolved workspace and clean; (6) verify via `filepath.Rel` that the result does not start with `..` or equal `..`; (7) attempt `filepath.EvalSymlinks` on the candidate — if successful, re-verify with `filepath.Rel`; if `EvalSymlinks` fails (path does not exist), return the already-verified candidate path.\n345: \n346: #### Scenario: Simple relative path\n347: \n348: - **GIVEN** `workspaceDir=\"/workspace\"` and input path `\"subdir/file.txt\"`\n349: - **WHEN** `sanitizePath` is called\n350: - **THEN** the result is `/workspace/subdir/file.txt` with no error\n351: \n352: #### Scenario: Directory traversal blocked\n353: \n354: - **GIVEN** input path `\"../../etc/passwd\"`\n355: - **WHEN** `sanitizePath` is called\n356: - **THEN** an error is returned indicating access denied / workspace jail violation\n357: \n358: #### Scenario: Absolute path is stripped\n359: \n360: - **GIVEN** input path `\"/etc/passwd\"`\n361: - **WHEN** `sanitizePath` is called\n362: - **THEN** the leading `/` is stripped and the path is treated as `etc/passwd` relative to workspace\n363: \n364: #### Scenario: Symlink inside workspace allowed\n365: \n366: - **GIVEN** a symlink inside the workspace pointing to another location inside the workspace\n367: - **WHEN** `sanitizePath` resolves the path\n368: - **THEN** `EvalSymlinks` succeeds and the resolved path is re-verified to be inside the workspace\n369: \n370: #### Scenario: Symlink escape blocked\n371: \n372: - **GIVEN** a symlink inside the workspace pointing to a location outside the workspace\n373: - **WHEN** `sanitizePath` resolves the path\n374: - **THEN** the re-verification via `filepath.Rel` detects the `..` prefix and returns an access denied error\n375: \n376: #### Scenario: Non-existent path inside workspace allowed\n377: \n378: - **GIVEN** input path `\"new-file.txt\"` that does not yet exist but is inside the workspace\n379: - **WHEN** `sanitizePath` is called\n380: - **THEN** `EvalSymlinks` fails (path does not exist), but the already-verified candidate path is returned\n381: \n382: #### Scenario: Empty workspace directory\n383: \n384: - **GIVEN** `workspaceDir` is empty string\n385: - **WHEN** `sanitizePath` is called\n386: - **THEN** an error `workspace directory not initialized` is returned\n387: \n388: ### Request/Response type definitions\n389: \n390: The system SHALL define the following structs with exact JSON tags:\n391: \n392: ```go\n393: type ExecuteRequest struct {\n394:     Command    []string          `json:\"command\" binding:\"required\"`\n395:     Timeout    string            `json:\"timeout\"`\n396:     WorkingDir string            `json:\"working_dir\"`\n397:     Env        map[string]string `json:\"env\"`\n398: }\n399: \n400: type ExecuteResponse struct {\n401:     Stdout    string    `json:\"stdout\"`\n402:     Stderr    string    `json:\"stderr\"`\n403:     ExitCode  int       `json:\"exit_code\"`\n404:     Duration  float64   `json:\"duration\"`\n405:     StartTime time.Time `json:\"start_time\"`\n406:     EndTime   time.Time `json:\"end_time\"`\n407: }\n408: \n409: type FileInfo struct {\n410:     Path     string    `json:\"path\"`\n411:     Size     int64     `json:\"size\"`\n412:     Mode     string    `json:\"mode\"`\n413:     Modified time.Time `json:\"modified\"`\n414: }\n415: \n416: type UploadFileRequest struct {\n417:     Path    string `json:\"path\" binding:\"required\"`\n418:     Content string `json:\"content\" binding:\"required\"`\n419:     Mode    string `json:\"mode\"`\n420: }\n421: \n422: type FileEntry struct {\n423:     Name     string    `json:\"name\"`\n424:     Size     int64     `json:\"size\"`\n425:     Modified time.Time `json:\"modified\"`\n426:     Mode     string    `json:\"mode\"`\n427:     IsDir    bool      `json:\"is_dir\"`\n428: }\n429: \n430: type ListFilesResponse struct {\n431:     Files []FileEntry `json:\"files\"`\n432: }\n433: ```\n434: \n435: #### Scenario: ExecuteRequest binding\n436: \n437: - **GIVEN** JSON body `{\"command\": [\"ls\", \"-la\"], \"timeout\": \"10s\", \"working_dir\": \"src\", \"env\": {\"GOOS\": \"linux\"}}`\n438: - **WHEN** `ShouldBindJSON` is called\n439: - **THEN** all fields are populated correctly with their respective types\n440: \n441: #### Scenario: ExecuteResponse serialization\n442: \n443: - **GIVEN** a completed command execution\n444: - **WHEN** the response is serialized to JSON\n445: - **THEN** all six fields (`stdout`, `stderr`, `exit_code`, `duration`, `start_time`, `end_time`) are present with correct types\n446: \n447: ### Requirement: Constants\n448: \n449: The system SHALL define the following constants:\n450: \n451: | Name | Value | Meaning |\n452: |------|-------|---------|\n453: | `TimeoutExitCode` | `124` | Exit code when context deadline exceeded |\n454: | `MaxBodySize` | `32 << 20` (32 MiB) | `http.MaxBytesReader` cap after JWT check |\n455: | `PublicKeyEnvVar` | `\"PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY\"` | Env var for PEM public key |\n456: | `maxFileMode` | `0777` | Maximum allowed file mode in `parseFileMode` |\n457: \n458: #### Scenario: Timeout exit code value\n459: \n460: - **GIVEN** a command times out\n461: - **WHEN** the exit code is set\n462: - **THEN** it equals `124`\n463: \n464: #### Scenario: Max body size value\n465: \n466: - **GIVEN** `MaxBodySize` is referenced\n467: - **WHEN** its value is inspected\n468: - **THEN** it equals `33554432` (32 MiB)\n469: \n470: ### Requirement: Server struct and lifecycle\n471: \n472: The system SHALL define a `Server` struct with fields: `engine *gin.Engine`, `config Config`, `authManager *AuthManager`, `startTime time.Time`, `workspaceDir string`. `NewServer` SHALL set `startTime = time.Now()`, initialize the auth manager, load the public key, resolve the workspace, register routes, and construct the `http.Server`. `Run` SHALL call `http.Server.ListenAndServe()`.\n473: \n474: #### Scenario: NewServer initializes all fields\n475: \n476: - **GIVEN** a valid `Config` and `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` set\n477: - **WHEN** `NewServer(config)` is called\n478: - **THEN** all five struct fields are non-zero/non-nil: `engine`, `config`, `authManager`, `startTime`, `workspaceDir`\n479: \n480: #### Scenario: startTime is set at construction\n481: \n482: - **GIVEN** `NewServer` is called at time T\n483: - **WHEN** `server.startTime` is inspected\n484: - **THEN** it equals approximately T (within test tolerance)\n485: \n486: #### Scenario: Run starts listening\n487: \n488: - **GIVEN** a valid `Server` with `config.Port = 8080`\n489: - **WHEN** `server.Run()` is called\n490: - **THEN** the HTTP server begins listening on `:8080`\n\n(End of file - total 490 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-015: PicoD 命令执行 API — Delta Spec\n\n## Context\n\n- **Module:** `pkg/picod`, `cmd/picod`\n- **Language:** Go\n- **Size:** M\n- **Base specs:** `code-execution/spec.md`, `code-execution/design.md`, `deployment/client-go.md`\n\n## Delta Requirements\n\n### Requirement: Server configuration and startup\n\nThe system SHALL define a `Config` struct with `Port int` and `Workspace string` fields. The system SHALL parse CLI flags `-port` (default `8080`) and `-workspace` (default `\"\"`). If `workspace` is empty, the workspace root SHALL be resolved to the current working directory via `os.Getwd()`; failure to resolve CWD SHALL be fatal. The HTTP server SHALL use `ReadHeaderTimeout` of 10 seconds. Gin SHALL run in `ReleaseMode` with `gin.Logger()` and `gin.Recovery()` as global middleware.\n\n#### Scenario: Defaults from CLI\n\n- **GIVEN** `-port` and `-workspace` flags use program defaults\n- **WHEN** the binary starts\n- **THEN** `Port` defaults to `8080`, `Workspace` is empty (resolved to CWD at runtime)","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_alibaba-cn-qwen3.6-plus_20260410T073331Z/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775839404395,"end":1775839404400}}}}
